Yes, I think that makes sense, although you will obviously lose the interannual variability which may be important. For example, if every fourth year the rains fail and there is a large shortfall which is subsequently made up in the intervening years, can we say that the system is sustainable? Perhaps from a long term perspective, but if farmers' crops are failing every fourth year because the canals aren't running and their wells are not deep enough to abstract water then they may not agree.

